Every Angular developer eventually asks the same question: “Do I need NgRx?”
The answer, more often than not, is no.
Not because NgRx is bad. It’s excellent for large-scale applications with complex async workflows, strict unidirectional data flow, and teams that benefit from enforced architectural patterns. But for the majority of Angular applications — dashboard apps, CRUD tools, content management systems — two RxJS primitives handle 80% of state management needs without any additional library.
Those primitives are BehaviorSubject and shareReplay().
I’ve been using both throughout Reactive Lab, my interactive RxJS playground, without fully appreciating that they represent two different state management strategies. This article makes those strategies explicit.

The State Management Problem
Angular components are temporary. They’re created when the user navigates to a route and destroyed when the user navigates away. But the data they display — the current user, the theme preference, the shopping cart — needs to survive across those navigations.
This creates a fundamental tension:

• Components are short-lived — they come and go

• State is long-lived — it persists across component lifecycles

• Multiple components need the same state simultaneously
Without a centralized approach, each component fetches its own copy of the data. Three components displaying user information means three HTTP calls for the same user. The results might arrive at different times, causing inconsistent UI. And when the user updates their profile, only one component knows about it — the others show stale data.
This is the problem state management solves. The question is how much machinery we need.

The BehaviorSubject Service Pattern
The Problem We’re Solving
Consider a typical Angular app with three components that all need the current user’s data:
┌─────────────────────────────────────────────────────┐
│ App Shell │
│ ┌────────────── ┐ ┌────────────────────────────┐ │
│ │ Sidebar │ │ Main Content │ │
│ │ │ │ │ │
│ │ Role: ??? │ │ ┌────────────────────── ┐ │ │
│ │ │ │ │ Profile Page │ │ │
│ └────────────── ┘ │ │ │ │ │
│ ┌────────────── ┐ │ │ Name: ??? │ │ │
│ │ Header │ │ │ Email: ??? │ │ │
│ │ "Hello ???" │ │ └────────────────────── ┘ │ │
│ └────────────── ┘ └────────────────────────────┘ │
└─────────────────────────────────────────────────────┘Without centralized state, each component fetches user data independently. That means three HTTP calls for the same data. Worse — the Header might show the user’s name from a response that arrived at a different time than the Sidebar’s response, causing inconsistent UI.
We need a single place that holds the current user, notifies all interested components when it changes, and immediately gives the current value to any component that shows up later (e.g., when the user navigates to the Profile page after already logging in).
The Whiteboard Analogy
Think of a BehaviorSubject inside a service as a whiteboard in an office.
The whiteboard always has something written on it — that’s the current state. It starts with an initial message (the seed value). When someone updates the board, everyone in the room immediately sees the change. And when a new person walks into the office, they can read the board immediately — they don’t need to wait for the next update.
The whiteboard is owned by the office (the service), not by any individual person (a component). People come and go. The whiteboard stays.
┌─────────────────────────┐
│ AuthService │
│ │
login() ──────► │ ┌───────────────────┐ │
│ │ BehaviorSubject │ │
logout() ─────► │ │ │ │
│ │ currentUser$$ │ │
│ │ ┌─────────────┐ │ │
│ │ │ User | null │ │ │ ──► HeaderComponent
│ │ └─────────────┘ │ │ ──► SidebarComponent
│ └───────────────────┘ │ ──► ProfileComponent
│ │
│ (service lives forever)│
└─────────────────────────┘Building the Service Step by Step
Here’s an AuthService that uses this pattern. Let's build it piece by piece.
Step 1 — The state holder. A private BehaviorSubject holds the current user. It starts with null (no one logged in yet). Only the service can write to it.
// Private — only the service can call .next()
private currentUser$$ = new BehaviorSubject<User | null>(null);Step 2 — The public read-only stream. Components subscribe to this. They can read, but they cannot push values into it. The $$ (double dollar) convention marks the writable Subject; $ (single dollar) marks the read-only Observable.
// Public — components subscribe to this
currentUser$ = this.currentUser$$.asObservable();Step 3 — Methods that update state. Only the service decides when and how state changes. Components call these methods; the service pushes new values via .next().
login(credentials: Credentials): Observable<User> {
return this.http.post<User>('/api/login', credentials).pipe(
tap(user => this.currentUser$$.next(user)) // push to the whiteboard
);
}logout(): void {
this.currentUser$$.next(null); // clear the whiteboard
}
Step 4 — Derived state. Computed Observables that transform the primary state — no separate storage needed. This is the same idea behind NgRx selectors, without the library.
isLoggedIn$ = this.currentUser$.pipe(
map(user => user !== null)
);The complete service:
@Injectable({ providedIn: 'root' })
export class AuthService {
private currentUser$$ = new BehaviorSubject<User | null>(null); currentUser$ = this.currentUser$$.asObservable();
isLoggedIn$ = this.currentUser$.pipe(
map(user => user !== null)
);
login(credentials: Credentials): Observable<User> {
return this.http.post<User>('/api/login', credentials).pipe(
tap(user => this.currentUser$$.next(user))
);
}
logout(): void {
this.currentUser$$.next(null);
}
}
This service enforces a clear ownership boundary: the service owns the state, components consume it. Components can subscribe to currentUser$ but cannot call .next() — they can read the whiteboard but only the service can write on it.
Why BehaviorSubject and Not a Plain Subject?
This is the critical design choice, and understanding it requires knowing how RxJS Subjects differ.
A plain Subject is like a live radio broadcast — if you tune in late, you miss whatever was said before. It has no memory. A BehaviorSubject is like a TV channel with a "last frame" buffer — when you switch to the channel, you immediately see what's currently on screen, then continue watching live.
Subject (no memory):
login() emits "Alice" ──► HeaderComponent sees "Alice" ✅
SidebarComponent sees "Alice" ✅
... user navigates to /profile ...
ProfileComponent subscribes ──► gets NOTHING ❌
(missed the login event)BehaviorSubject (remembers current value):
login() emits "Alice" ──► HeaderComponent sees "Alice" ✅
SidebarComponent sees "Alice" ✅
... user navigates to /profile ...
ProfileComponent subscribes ──► gets "Alice" immediately ✅
(current value replayed)In Angular apps with routing, “late subscriber” is the default case, not the exception. Most components are created after the state they need was last updated. BehaviorSubject handles this naturally.
🔗 See it live: The Reactive Lab Subjects demo lets you emit values, then add a late subscriber to see this exact difference side by side — Subject (gets nothing), BehaviorSubject (gets the latest), and ReplaySubject (gets the last N).
Press enter or click to view image in full size

Subjects demo after emitting 3 values and adding late subscribers, showing Subject panel with 0 late entries, BehaviorSubject with 1, ReplaySubject with 2Multiple Components, One Source of Truth
With the service in place, every component subscribes to the same stream:
// HeaderComponent — shows user name
this.authService.currentUser$.subscribe(user => {
this.userName = user?.name ?? 'Guest';
});// SidebarComponent - shows user role
this.authService.currentUser$.subscribe(user => {
this.userRole = user?.role ?? 'none';
});
// ProfileComponent - shows full user details
this.authService.currentUser$.subscribe(user => {
this.userProfile = user;
});
When login() calls this.currentUser$$.next(user), all three components update simultaneously. One source of truth. No duplicate HTTP calls. No stale data.
login("Alice")
│
▼
┌──────────────┐
│ currentUser$$│──► .next("Alice")
└──────┬───────┘
│
┌────┼────┐
▼ ▼ ▼
Header Sidebar Profile
"Alice" "admin" { name, email, ... }The service owns the state lifecycle (it lives forever as a providedIn: 'root' singleton). Components own their display lifecycle (created/destroyed by routing). The Observable subscription connects them without coupling them — a separation of concerns that becomes increasingly important as the app grows.

The shareReplay Pattern — Caching Without Manual Management
BehaviorSubject is perfect for state we actively manage — state that changes in response to user actions like login, logout, theme toggle, or cart updates. We call .next() to push new values.
But there’s another category of state: data we fetch once and cache. Application configuration. Feature flags. A user profile that doesn’t change during a session. Static reference data.
For this category, BehaviorSubject works but feels like overkill. We'd need to:

• Create a BehaviorSubject with an initial null

• Write a load() method that makes the HTTP call

• Subscribe to the HTTP call inside the service

• Push the result into the BehaviorSubject via .next()

• Handle the initial null in every consuming component

• Decide who triggers load() and when
That’s a lot of manual orchestration for “fetch once, use everywhere.”
shareReplay Does It in One Line
@Injectable({ providedIn: 'root' })
export class ConfigService {
config$ = this.http.get<AppConfig>('/api/config').pipe(
shareReplay(1)
); constructor(private http: HttpClient) {}
}
That’s the entire service. No BehaviorSubject. No .next(). No load() method. No initial null to handle.
What happens:

• First component subscribes → HTTP call fires automatically (lazy execution)

• Second component subscribes → receives the cached result instantly (no new HTTP call)

• Third component subscribes → receives the cached result instantly

• No one subscribes → no HTTP call is ever made (truly lazy)
Proving It in Reactive Lab
In the Reactive Lab shareReplay demo, this behavior is made visible through two side-by-side panels backed by the same simulated API call. The difference between them is a single line in the pipeline:
// Raw source — every subscription triggers a new "HTTP call"
this.rawSource$ = this.createFakeApi('raw');// Shared source - one execution, cached and replayed
this.sharedSource$ = this.createFakeApi('shared').pipe(
shareReplay(1)
);
The simulated API is just an Observable that increments a counter and emits after a delay — exactly what an HTTP call does, but visible:
private createFakeApi(panel: string): Observable<string[]> {
return new Observable<string[]>((subscriber) => {
// This runs on EVERY subscription for raw,
// but only ONCE for shareReplay
if (panel === 'raw') {
this.rawHttpCount++;
this.addLog('❌', `HTTP call #${this.rawHttpCount} triggered (duplicate!)`, 'fetch');
} else {
this.sharedHttpCount++;
this.addLog('✅', `HTTP call #${this.sharedHttpCount} triggered`, 'fetch');
}
// Simulate network delay
const timer = setTimeout(() => {
subscriber.next(['User Profile', 'Preferences', 'Settings']);
subscriber.complete();
}, 1500);
// Cleanup on unsubscribe
return () => clearTimeout(timer);
});
}Adding a subscriber to each panel is identical — both just call .subscribe():
// Panel 1 — no sharing
const sub = this.rawSource$!.subscribe((data) => {
entry.status = 'received';
entry.data = data;
});// Panel 2 - with shareReplay(1)
const sub = this.sharedSource$!.subscribe((data) => {
entry.status = 'received';
entry.data = data;
});
The result tells the whole story. The left panel (without shareReplay) shows the HTTP call counter growing with every subscriber added — 3 subscribers, 3 network requests. The right panel (with shareReplay(1)) shows the counter staying at 1 regardless of how many subscribers are added. The
